'''aMSN'''<ref name=linuxmag>{{cite web|url=http://www.linux-magazine.com/w3/issue/82/aMSN_in_Linux.pdf |title=aMSN in Linux on Linux Magazine |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref> is a free [[Windows Live Messenger]] clone. aMSN attempts to emulate the look and feel of Windows Live Messenger, and supports many of its features. It has been downloaded approximately 40 million times as of January 2011, making it the 21st most downloaded project on SourceForge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sourceforge.net/top/topalltime.php?type=downloads |title=Top Downloads - For all time, updated daily |publisher=Sourceforge.net |date= |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref>

aMSN is available for any system that supports [[Tcl/Tk]] 8.4 or higher, including Microsoft Windows, Macintosh and any UNIX/Linux variant, including Maemo (Nokia's internet tablets) and OpenSolaris.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sun.systemnews.com/articles/118/2/OpenSolaris/19046 |title=aMSN Messenger Clone Ported to OpenSolaris |publisher=Sun SystemNews |date=2007-12-10 |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref> A portable version for Windows is available by PortableApps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portableapps.com/apps/internet/amsn_portable |title=aMSN Portable |publisher=PortableApps.com |date=2011-01-13 |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref>

== History ==
aMSN was based on a previous application named Compu's Messenger (ccmsn), released on September 21, 2001 by Dave Mifsud. Features in this application were quite limited and development seemed to be stopped. Alvaro Iradier made a fork of the development with his own version, aMSN (Alvaro's Messenger). At the time Didimo E. Grimaldo was also working on his own branch of ccMSN until both Alvaro and Didimo heard of each other in a development forum and decided to merge their improvements into one version. The first version of aMSN was released on May 22, 2002 on [[Sourceforge]].

After several successful releases of their join effort, Didimo E. Grimaldo decided to take leave as a developer due to other pressing responsibilities and lack of time. ccMSN/aMSN was in fact the last of several free and open source projects in which Didimo worked.

More developers joined the project, like Philippe G. Khalaf and later Youness Alaoui. Today the project keeps going thanks to the effort and help of an increasing number of developers, translators, and designers.

aMSN is well-known for quickly implementing most of the official client's features, often being the only third-party client that supports them. For example, it is the only client that supports video conferencing on Mac.<ref>{{cite web|last=Santos |first=Elena |url=http://amsn.en.softonic.com/mac |title=Review on Softonic |publisher=Amsn.en.softonic.com |date=2010-12-09 |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref> It has been reviewed by many software-specialized websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.softpedia.com/reviews/linux/aMSN-Review-20294.shtml |title=Linux software reviews on Softpedia |publisher=Softpedia.com |date= |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.makeuseof.com/tag/6-alternative-chat-applications-for-msn-on-mac-os-x/ |title=6 Alternative Chat Applications for MSN on Mac OS X |publisher=Makeuseof.com |date=2008-04-11 |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref> Its releases have appeared on several well-known blogs,<ref>{{cite web|author=Written by M. Zinoune |url=http://www.unixmen.com/news-today/535-new-version-of-amsn-is-available-with-new-features |title=New version of aMSN is available with new features |publisher=Unixmen |date=2009-11-11 |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geekets.com/2009/11/25/amsn-una-alternativa-gratuita-para-el-msn-messenger/ |title=aMSN una alternativa gratuita para el Msn Messenger |publisher=Geekets |date=2009-11-25 |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://linux.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=05/12/26/1911248 |title=Slashdot &#124; aMSN 0.95 released |publisher=Linux.slashdot.org |date=2005-12-26 |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mann |first=Justin |url=http://www.techspot.com/news/19901-amsn-095-released-after-more-than-a-year.html |title=aMSN 0.95 released after more than a year - TechSpot News |publisher=Techspot.com |date=2005-12-26 |accessdate=2011-10-14}}</ref> its developers have been interviewed<ref>[http://www.osnews.com/story/15165/Interview_Alvaro_J_Iradier_AMS